 or JACKSONVILLE\nJacksonville, March 21\u2014(Special)\u2014\nCamp W. B. Martin of this place will\nbe largely represented at the Cot\nfederate Reunion at Birmingham In\nJune.\nMr. Ferre), of Annleton has moved\nto Jacksonville, and occupies the\nresidence lately occupied by the\nBaptist minister.\nMr. and Mrs. E. T. Ide, of St. Johns\nbury. Vermont, are hero visiting their\nson, Ooorge P. Ide and family. Mr.\nMe le a brother of Hen. Henry C.\nIde. late Governor General of the\nPhilippines.\nLieutenant James C. Williams, a\ngraduate ef the United States Military\nAcademy at West Point. Is spending\nhis production leave In Jacksonville\nwith hls family. He expects to be as\nsigned to service with the 2\u00abth Infan\ntry now In the Philippines, and will\nprobably report at San Francisco, May\n14th. and sail for the Philippines Junt\n6th.\nThe Jacksonville Card Club has sus\npended their meetings until after Lent.\nThe. organisation of Mountain Climb\ning parties will soon be In vogue, and\na number of our people are preparing\nto go to Sulphur Springs, a local health\nresort, this summer.\nReed TyeeCe platterwi, and sec bow\nboldly aad fearlessly bo speaks on the\nIssaes that vitally concern the city.\nAN OCEAN RACE.\nAn American Liner Defeats Preach\nSteamer La Tmsralae.\nNew York. March 21.\u2014Swinging by\nBandy Hook lata today with har pro\npellers churning a foamy wake that\nlaid the following course for her beat\nen rival, the eteamshlp St. Louis, of the\nAmerican Line, defeated the French\nliner La Touratne In one ef the moot\nexciting ocean raees In trans-Atlanttc\nsteamship travel.\nThe La Touralne left Havre, France,\nabout I o'clock last Saturday morning\nand the St. Louie departed from Cher\nbourg eight hours later on her voyage\nacrose the Atlantic.\nThe American liner elowly crept up\non the La Touralne and on Thursday\nafternoon the two ships raced along\nprow and prow. Late that night the\nSt. Louie forged ahead.\nLa Touralne hung tenaciously to the\nAmerican's trail and through the\nsmoke of the St. Louis was generally\nvisible, the passengers on the French\nmen did not again catch a glimpse of\nthe St. Louie until La Touralne passed\nSandy Hook this afternoon, an hour\nand thirty-six minutes behind the\nAmerican steamer.\nVate for Ouster and Faithful Ser\nvice.\nOPTIMISTIC SENTIMENTS*\nPruaalaeat Statesmen Speak at College\nFraternity Dlaaer.\nNew York. March 21\u2014Two United\nState* Senator*. W ,E. Borah, of Idaho,\nand Norrl* Brown, of Nebraska and\none member of the National House of\nRepresentative*. Henry Sherman\nBoutell. of Illinois, were the guests\nof honor and chief speakers at the\ndinner of the Beta Theta PI Club at\nthe Hotel Astor tonight.\nOptimistic sentiments as to the\nearly return of prosperity to the\ncountry and expressions of confidence\nthat legislation of recent years would\nhave a far reaching and lasting effect\nfor the good of the nation, was the\nspirit of the speeches.\n\u2018Equality before the law,\" was Sena\ntor Borah's subject and he declared\nfor a revision of the tariff, urging the\nformation of a tariff commission which\nshould bring its report before Con\ngress for Intelligent action by that\nbody. Senator Borah talked of the\nrecent panic and Its lessons, while\nMr. Boutell took recent legislation and\nits good effect* as a subject.\nThe Mayflower Sails.\nNew Orleans. March 21.\u2014The United\nStates yacht Mayflower sailed from\nVicksburg. Miss., where Mrs. Roose\nvelt will board the boat for a trip\ndown the Mississippi River. Lieuten\nant Commander Thomas Snowder was\nin command of the Mayflower, having\nrelieved Commander Carl T. Vogelge\nsang since the Mayflower's arrival here\nthree days ago.\nFor health's sake\u2014Champagne Cel\nery\u2014 Demonstration Mnaday.\nBrock Grocery Co.\nTuscaloosa County Court.\nTuscaloosa. March 21\u2014(Special)\nThe County Court had a very busy\nsession this week, every day being\nwell occupied. At adjournment yes\nterday evening thirty-six cases had\nbeen disposed of and there will be\nseveral more concluded today.\nTyson Is lu favor of the present gcu\nrratlen turning over to Ita posterity a\nbeautiful city out of dcht; and not\nshifting the burden to a future gener\nation\nALARMED BY SHOT\nThe mound of m pistol shot mt \u00ab:M\no'clock last night oo Court stroot\norcmtcd excitement In the down town\ndistrict. It won soon learned, however,\nby the big crowd that rushed to the\nscene, that the revolver of Officer Hill,\nof the police force, had been acci\ndentally discharged In front of Todd's\ndun Store, and the temporary excite\nment abated as suddenly as It had\narisen.\nThe Incident, happening as It did.\nIn the time Immediately preoedlng\nelection was the cause of great alarm.\nImmediately following the shot came\na huge crowd pouring across the\nsquare and collecting In front of\nTodd's Oun Store. With curiosity they\nsought to ascertain who was killed\nand how many were wounded, and\nvarious other details that would have\nbeen harrowing If true. It did not\ntake the crowd a long time to disperse\nafter learning the facts.\nThe accident happened this way. Of\nficer Watts .entered Todd's Oun Store\nshortly after o'clock last night to\nserve a warrant charging Captain\nTodd with assault and battery. Cap\ntain Todd upon presentation of the\nwarrant refused compliance, and Is\nsaid to have struck the officer. The\nofficer then blew his whistle for as\nsistance.\nMeanwhile nearby officers were run\nning to his assistance, and one of them\nIn so doing dropped his pistol upon the\ngrating. Then followed the discharge,\nthe excitement, and the crowd. In a\nfew minutes, however, things had\nquieted down.\nCaptain Tcdd was taken to head\nquarters by Officers Watts and Canty\nwithout further trouble. The occur\nrence had been greatly magnlfled\nthrough the spirit of high tension In\ncident to election times, and by the\nunfortunate discharge of a revolver. No\nharm was done.\nTysea is la favor of tkr preseal goo\neratlea turning over to Its pootcrlty a\nbeautiful city out at deht\u00bb aad Ml\nshifting the bardra to a future geaer\natloa.\nCABLES CHSM MATCH.\nAre la UM Over BiiHrh\nPhiladelphia. March 11\u2014The Ameri\ncana had a decided advantage tonight\nwhen play In the eabla ehere match\nbetween teams representing Oxford\nand Cambridge of England and those\nrepresenting Columbia. Harvard, Yale,\nPrinceton, Cornell, Brown and Penn\nsylvania was adjourned.\nAccording to the rules agreed upon,\nthe play which had etarted at A m..\nceased at p. m. Four games had\nbeen decided and of these the Amer\nicans had won two. loot ono and\ndrawn one, giving them a. score of l\n1-2 to 1- 1-2 for their British oppon\nents. Draws were offered te the\nBritons on the two unfinished games,\nhut the latter declined, preferring that\nthey be adjudicated upon by Refers*\nWalter Penn Shipley of this city., Mr.\nShipley would not give hie decision\non the spot and staled It might be a\nweek befere hie opinion was given.\nExperts In attendance on the games\ngave It as their opinion tonight that\nthe Americans would retain their lead\nafter the adjudication and In that way\nwin the match and the Rice trophy.\nThe Americans who won their games\nwere Louis J. Wolff, of Columbia, and\nC. Williams, of Princeton, W. H.\nHughes, of Pennsylvania, was beaten\non the tap board by N. J. Reughton.\nof Oxford. J. B. Johnstan. of Har\nvard. drew hie game with B. H.^H.\nStower. of Cambridge, while tha game\nbetween H. Blumberg. of Columbia,\nand H. Lob, of Oxford, and that be\ntween L. Ash. of Pennsylvania, and\nC O. Woodhouae, of Cambridge, re\nmained unfinished and In <H*PuJe.\nThe match was played In the hall\nof the Houston Club and Inna Court\nHotel, London.\nAt the Majestic Thsatrs. Tuesday\nevs\u2014the Only Revolving/ Blectrleel\nAdvertising Tower In the world, pat\nented by J. T. Moncrlef of thie city.\nWill be ehlpped In a few days to\nChicago. Detroit. Philadelphia. Now\nYork etc., a* a theatrical attraction\nand for interested capitalists to see.\nAdv. _\nMAY DEiPORT REFUGEES.\nRefnsa to Olva Pledgea to G\u00bbms\nmrat to Return Home.\nPort au Prince. Haytl. March 21\u2014\nGeneral Antonelr Flrmin. the leader\nof the recent Insurrection In Hsyti\nand the other revolutionists, who have\nbeen refugees In the French consulate\nat Gonalvea. for the past two months,\nembarked today on the French cruiser\nD'Estrees. which proceeded for St.\nThomas\nThe refugees In the legations at\nPort Au Prince continue to refuse to\ngive pledges to the government that\nthey will return to their homes If\nreleased and It probably will be ne\ncessary to deport all of them under\ndiplomatic protection.\nFalthfal Ser\nVete far\nvice.\nSENSATION CREATED.\nReported Conspiracy To AhmhIuO\nORHali.\nGuatemala City. March 21.\u2014A eensa\ntion has been caused here because or\nthe circulation of an open letter ad\ndressed to President Cabrera and pur\nnortlng to convey Information that a\nconspiracy had been hatched In the\nRepublic of Salvador, having for its\nobject the assassination of President\nCabrera and President Figueroa of\nSalvador.\nThe letter states that a large sum\nof money had been advanced by prom\ninent personages to aid in carrying out\nthe plan._\nTyson stands for the highest social,\nmoral sad commercial development of\nthe City Montgomery.\nTOLSTOI HAS RELAPSE.\nNoted Russian Author SoRero Prom\nLack of Strength.\nSt Petersburg. March 21.\u2014A dis\noatch received here from Yasnaya Po\nllnya. says that Count Tolstoi, who is\n111 with influenza, has puttered a re\n18 Yesterday the famous Russian author\nwas better and he worked on a hook of\nreadings for the peasantry and trans\nlations from Victor Hugo, but today\nhis condition was not ao good. The\ngraviety of his illness Is not stated,\nbut it Is said that he suffers from lack\nofstre ngth, arising from the contin\nued strain of his work. He refuses as\nalways to follow the advice of his doc\n